in vertebrate species.\" [GOC:krc, PMID:17786051]\n7209:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this term is a molecular functions.\n7210-property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27438\" xsd:anyURI\n7211:is_obsolete: true\n7212-created_by: krc\n7213-creation_date: 2009-04-28T10:29:37Z\n--\n7219-def: \"OBSOLETE. A tRNA exon ligation process in which the splice junction phosphate is derived from exogenous GTP. This type of ligation to rejoin the 5' and 3' exons of a tRNA is observed in the yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae where the ligation reaction also produces a 2'-phosphate at the splice junction which is subsequently removed as part of the ligation process.\" [GOC:krc, PMID:18217203, PMID:9299409]\n7220:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this term is a molecular function\n7221-property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27438\" xsd:anyURI\n7222:is_obsolete: true\n7223-consider: GO:0000968\n7224-created_by: krc\n--\n7231-def: \"OBSOLETE. A tRNA exon ligation process in which the splice junction phosphate is derived from the 2',3' cyclic phosphate at the 3'-end of the 5'-exon. This type of ligation to rejoin the 5' and 3' exons of a tRNA is observed in wheat, Chlamydomonas, and vertebrate species including humans.\" [GOC:krc, PMID:17786051, PMID:18217203, PMID:9299409]\n7232:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this term is a molecular function.\n7233-property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27438\" xsd:anyURI\n7234:is_obsolete: true\n7235-consider: GO:0000968\n7236-created_by: krc\n--\n7417-def: \"OBSOLETE. Binding to a protein or protein complex, to modulate transcription. A protein binding transcription factor may or may not also interact with the template nucleic acid (either DNA or RNA) as well.\" [GOC:txnOH]\n7418:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this concept is partly covered by other concepts in the ontology and usage has been inconsistent.\n7419-synonym: \"protein binding transcription factor activity\" EXACT []\n7420-synonym: \"transcription factor activity\" BROAD []\n7421-property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/16053\" xsd:anyURI\n7422:is_obsolete: true\n7423-consider: GO:0005515\n7424-consider: GO:0140110\n--\n7432-def: \"OBSOLETE. Binding to a specific transcription factor, which may be a single protein or a complex, in order to modulate transcription. A protein binding transcription factor may or may not also interact with the template nucleic acid (either DNA or RNA) as well.\" [GOC:txnOH]\n7433:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this concept is partly covered by other concepts in the ontology and usage has been inconsistent.\n7434-synonym: \"transcription factor binding transcription factor activity\" EXACT []\n7435-property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/16053\" xsd:anyURI\n7436:is_obsolete: true\n7437-consider: GO:0008134\n7438-consider: GO:0140110\n--\n7446-def: \"OBSOLETE. Binding to an RNA polymerase in order to modulate transcription. A protein binding transcription factor may or may not also interact with the template nucleic acid (either DNA or RNA) as well.\" [GOC:txnOH]\n7447:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this concept is partly covered by other concepts in the ontology and usage has been inconsistent.\n7448-synonym: \"core RNA polymerase binding transcription factor activity\" EXACT []\n7449-property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/16053\" xsd:anyURI\n7450:is_obsolete: true\n7451-consider: GO:0043175\n7452-consider: GO:0140110\n--\n7460-def: \"OBSOLETE. Binding to an RNA polymerase II (Pol II) complex, typically composed of twelve subunits, in order to modulate transcription. A protein binding transcription factor may or may not also interact with the template nucleic acid (either DNA or RNA) as well.\" [GOC:txnOH]\n7461:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this concept is partly covered by other concepts in the ontology and usage has been inconsistent.\n7462-synonym: \"core RNA polymerase II binding transcription factor activity\" EXACT []\n7463-property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/16053\" xsd:anyURI\n7464:is_obsolete: true\n7465-consider: GO:0000993\n7466-consider: GO:0140110\n--\n7572-def: \"OBSOLETE. Initiating the assembly of the RNA polymerase III pre-initiation complex by binding to a control sequence in the intragenic region. This allows to recruit TFIIIB to the DNA at a site centered approximately 26 base pairs upstream of the start site of transcription. For tRNA genes, TFIIIC first associates with DNA, and then recruits TFIIIB. For 5S rRNA genes, TFIIIA binds to DNA first, followed by TFIIIC, which then recruits TFIIIB.\" [GOC:txnOH-2018, PMID:12381659, PMID:23063749, PMID:27911719, Wikipedia:RNA_polymerase_III]\n7573:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this function is redundant with other terms, most often 'transcription co-regulator activity; GO:0003712'.\n7574-synonym: \"RNA polymerase III assembly factor activity\" RELATED []\n7575-synonym: \"RNA polymerase III assembly factor activity, TFIIIB recruiting\" RELATED []\n--\n7593-property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/18561\" xsd:anyURI\n7594:is_obsolete: true\n7595-created_by: krc\n7596-creation_date: 2010-08-18T05:53:32Z\n--\n7616-synonym: \"RNA polymerase III transcription factor binding transcription factor activity\" EXACT []\n7617:is_obsolete: true\n7618-created_by: krc\n7619-creation_date: 2010-08-18T06:24:07Z\n--\n7630-property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/31456\" xsd:anyURI\n7631:is_obsolete: true\n7632-consider: GO:0003712\n7633-consider: GO:0140463\n--\n7643-synonym: \"sequence-specific DNA binding RNA polymerase recruiting transcription factor activity\" EXACT []\n7644:is_obsolete: true\n7645-consider: GO:0140223\n7646-created_by: krc\n--\n7741-synonym: \"RNA polymerase III recruiting transcription factor activity\" EXACT []\n7742:is_obsolete: true\n7743-created_by: krc\n7744-creation_date: 2010-08-23T12:24:31Z\n--\n7750-def: \"OBSOLETE. Binding to an RNA polymerase III (Pol III) complex, typically composed of seventeen subunits, and with another protein, macromolecule, or complex, permitting those molecules to function in a coordinated way. Once recruited to an RNA polymerase III type 1 promoter by TFIIIA-type and TFIIIC-type factors, binds to DNA, recruits RNA polymerase III and facilitates the transition from the closed to the open complex.\" [GOC:txnOH-2018, PMID:12381659]\n7751:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that there is a single TFIIIB activity; this is not dependent on the promoter.\n7752-synonym: \"RNA polymerase III type 1 promoter polymerase recruiting transcription factor activity\" RELATED []\n7753:is_obsolete: true\n7754-created_by: krc\n7755-creation_date: 2010-08-23T12:50:20Z\n--\n7761-def: \"OBSOLETE. Binding to an RNA polymerase III (Pol III) complex, typically composed of seventeen subunits, and with another protein, macromolecule, or complex, permitting those molecules to function in a coordinated way. Once recruited to an RNA polymerase III type 2 promoter by a TFIIIC-type factor, binds to DNA, recruits RNA polymerase III and facilitates the transition from the closed to the open complex.\" [GOC:txnOH-2018, PMID:12381659]\n7762:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that there is a single TFIIIB activity; this is not dependent on the promoter.\n7763-synonym: \"RNA polymerase III type 2 promoter polymerase recruiting transcription factor activity\" RELATED []\n7764:is_obsolete: true\n7765-created_by: krc\n7766-creation_date: 2010-08-23T12:52:01Z\n--\n7773-synonym: \"RNA polymerase III type 3 promoter polymerase recruiting transcription factor activity\" RELATED []\n7774:is_obsolete: true\n7775-created_by: krc\n7776-creation_date: 2010-08-23T12:52:40Z\n--\n7793-def: \"OBSOLETE. Binding to an RNA polymerase III (Pol III) complex, typically composed of seventeen subunits, and with another protein, macromolecule, or complex, permitting those molecules to function in a coordinated way. Once recruited to an RNA polymerase III hybrid type promoter, binds to DNA, recruits RNA polymerase III and facilitates the transition from the closed to the open complex.\" [GOC:txnOH-2018, PMID:12381659]\n7794:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that there is a single TFIIIB activity; this is not dependent on the promoter.\n7795:is_obsolete: true\n7796-created_by: krc\n7797-creation_date: 2010-08-23T06:28:23Z\n--\n7878-def: \"OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the reaction: nucleoside triphosphate + RNA(n) = diphosphate + RNA(n+1). Utilizes a DNA template that contains an RNA polymerase I specific promoter to direct initiation and catalyzes DNA-template-directed extension of the 3'-end of an RNA strand by one nucleotide at a time. Can initiate a chain 'de novo'.\" [GOC:txnOH]\n7879:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this term is equivalent to DNA-directed 5'-3' RNA polymerase activity.\n7880-synonym: \"DNA-directed RNA polymerase activity involved in transcription from RNA polymerase I promoter\" EXACT []\n7881-property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/23779\" xsd:anyURI\n7882-property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/28520\" xsd:anyURI\n7883:is_obsolete: true\n7884-replaced_by: GO:0003899\n7885-created_by: krc\n--\n7892-def: \"OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the reaction: nucleoside triphosphate + RNA(n) = diphosphate + RNA(n+1). Utilizes a DNA template that contains an RNA polymerase II specific promoter to direct initiation and catalyses DNA-template-directed extension of the 3'-end of an RNA strand by one nucleotide at a time. Can initiate a chain 'd